text: I would add even more for the RNN, some mathematical derivations are recurrent in its derivations for example when applying asymptotic analysis. Higher order corrections depend on previous corrections. So not only for time series can RNN be used but in general for any recurant thing for which you can describe with mathematical precision.

author: @pritomroy2465
text: Learning with respect to statisticians and R users 1. Theory stat- Basic stat, probability, distribution, sampling distribution, Baise theory, ANOVA, sampling, time series analysis.  2. math- linear algebra, calculus, basic math(series).  3. ml models-  (inferential model) linear regression (multicollinearity, heteroscedasticity, autocorrelation) logistic regression, ARIMA for time series.  (black box model) decision trees, LDA, QDA, PCA, UMAP, spline regression, SVM, K-means, naive base CNN, NN, RNN Enhance ML accuracy Bagging (ensembling), Boosting, Kernel trick, lesso and ridge regression.  math for ml- gradient descent, gini impurity, cross-entropy, mse, estimation technique (least square, likelihood estimation), matrix derivative  4. R programming  data structure- basically vector and dataFrame manipulation, a little bit of matrix and list. It is highly recommended to go through all the data structure manipulation in R language and know the data types eg(character, numeric, logical,factor) basicFunctions- loop (for, while), if-else, creating functions and some built-in basic function.  5. Packages  data cleaning and visualization Tidyverse (this is a meta-package inside it we have) dplyr (king of data wrangling), ggplot2 (itself is a beast for visualization), stringr, forcats, reader, purrr etc etc  modeling Tidymodels (meta-packages for all ml API integrated) broom, parsnip, tune, workflow, yardstick, recipe etc etc  web apps and dashboard shiny (web app, interactive dashboard), plotly (interactive dashboard)  some useful packages Rmarkdown, skimr, lubridate  NB. I still can't recommend you some packages for the time series analysis as I still don't try this and I don't have an idea about database language like MySQL but you don't need to know about tablo if you are good at ggplot2 and shiny. My recommendation if you have the time like you are doing graduation on statistics or mathematics follow this. This is a lot more time-consuming but once you learn, you are going to save the day. Bsc. in Statistics, University of Dhaka.

author: @affanamin105
text: When you follow the data science learning path, you will easily get distracted to learn other interesting topics like deep learning, big data, distributed eco system (hadoop), hive, hbase, spark, Scala, Tableau, and etc.  Please do not start to learn every new terminologies; you came across.  My advice is to just stay focus, get your hands dirty with statistics, data ingestion, exploring, Data Visualization techniques, try to learn background knowledge of Machine learning algorithms, modeling, Understand the parameters to measure results and then move slowly towards complex topics.

You went ahead and tried to grab this opportunity where people actually have time to improve their skills and perhaps add some new skills to their skill set by monetizing your courses. I'm not sure what to say about that other than conveying my disappointment.   If this was done at any other time i would have totally understand the move. But it doesn't make sense at times like these where people are going out of their way to help each other. Anyways its your courses, its your materials, its your decision.

author: @raghav4296
text: TLDR;   1. Gain Python/R expertise 2. Libraries:  NumPy - Library, Indexing, Basic operation on Arrays, reshaping, broadcasting arrays, etc.  Pandas - In-depth understanding of Data pre-processing. Dataframes/Data series. Feature engineering. 3. Statistics:  Mean, Median, Mode  Normal and Standard distributions  Correlations  And all possible basic concepts that you could think of  No need to byheart formulas 4. Visualization libraries  - MatPlotLib  - Seaborn 5. Hands-on Exploratory Data analysis(EDA) - Try to find as much information from a given data set.  - Scaling down data - MinMax, Standard, LogNormal  - Record observations 6. Understanding ML algos: 15-20  - Understand theoretical concept + mathematically 7. Deployment:  - Deployment techniques on popular Public Cloud  - Flask & Django  -  8. Deep Learning  - 3 basic Neural Algos: Aritifical(ANN),Convolutional(CNN) & Recurrent(RNN)  - Advanced learning on CNN  - Deployment  - Popular libraries like TensorFlow, Keras, Pytorch 9. Databases:  - SQL for structured data  - MongoDB for unstructured data 10. Visualization:  - PowerBI  - Tableau  - Qlik Sense
